{
  "text": "SCF functions as a complex of Skp1, Cullin 1 and F-box proteins, which are thought to determine the specificity of binding proteins or degradation substrates [CITATION_1] . We next sought for an Fbox protein responsible for the meiotic function of SCF/Skp1 among eighteen F-box proteins reported to date (GeneDB; www. genedb.org/genedb/pombe/). Among deletion mutants of these F-box protein, we screened all viable strains for the one that reproduced the bent spindle seen in the skp1-a7 mutant. None showed a bent-spindle in MI, except for fbh1D (Fig. 4A) . Fbh1/ Fdh1 is a unique F-box protein, which has an UvrD/REP helicase domain at the C-terminus, in addition to the conserved F-box motif at the N-terminus [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . Fbh1 is known to process the recombination intermediates in mitosis [CITATION_4] and meiosis [CITATION_5] . The frequency of the appearance of a bent spindle at MI in the fbh1D mutant reached almost 40% (see Fig. 5C ), which was comparable to the percentage in the skp1-a7 mutant. Similarly to skp1-a7, fbh1D cells showed defects in chromosome disjunction (indicated by Taz1-2mCherry, Fig. 4B ). fbh1D cells also exhibited persistence of Rad22-mCherry foci during MI, like skp1-a7 cells (Fig. 4C) . Thus, the fbh1D mutant displayed nearly the same phenotype as the skp1-a7 mutant during meiosis.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "11118665",
    "[CITATION_2]": "15397156",
    "[CITATION_3]": "29667166",
